00:36.340 --> 00:38.020
And here are your hosts.

00:42.080 --> 00:49.220
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. You'll sometimes find that collectors of
science fiction and fantasy books are into comics also. In fact, collecting

00:49.220 --> 00:56.340
comics is becoming a more widespread hobby all the time, and often you'll find
collectible comics at a specialty store that handles science fiction, fantasy,

00:56.500 --> 01:04.340
and gaming material. Bob Wayne owns such a store in Fort Worth, Texas, called
Fantastic Worlds Bookstore, and he also collects comics. When he asked him how

01:04.340 --> 01:11.860
an interested newcomer might get into comic book collecting, he had some words
of caution. Well, the first recommendation I make to people, if they come in and

01:11.860 --> 01:22.120
say, I read that so-and-so comic book has gone up a thousand percent in two
years. What comic book would you recommend that I should start collecting? I

01:22.120 --> 01:33.100
tell people that they really shouldn't be buying comics unless they enjoy
reading comics. If there's nothing in that comic they enjoy reading, then

01:33.100 --> 01:42.480
they're making a mistake getting into comics because there are other things they
could invest money in that people will not laugh at you when you go to the bank

01:42.480 --> 01:50.040
and tell them that you want to use it for collateral. So comic books as an
investment is the kind of thing that's really been overplayed in the media to

01:50.040 --> 01:57.800
some extent. I mean, it sounds real good for the few comics that have
appreciated a great deal of value, but speaking from experience, a bank does not

01:57.800 --> 02:06.460
really think that that's the kind of collateral they want to hold for a loan. So
stocks and bonds still sound preferable to me as investments. But what if

02:06.460 --> 02:16.000
someone did take up comic book collecting? What about storing and preserving
them? If you're going to keep a comic book for a collection, it's important to

02:16.000 --> 02:31.700
handle it carefully. And if you're going to keep it, you should bag it up at
least in a plastic bag. If you have a comic book that's worth over $50, $100,

02:32.260 --> 02:42.440
you might want to invest in bags of a type of plastic in which a lot of the
things that would be in a plastic that would potentially cause the comic to

02:42.440 --> 02:50.740
deteriorate in 50 or 100 years would be neutralized. And if you want to go
further along, if you have comic books that are worth hundreds of dollars, there

02:50.740 --> 03:02.060
are things in the paper, the process of making pulp paper, that will eventually
cause it to rot. You can have the stuff deacidified. But there's no point in

03:02.060 --> 03:09.460
doing this with just every comic book on the shelf. And actually, if you don't
have any errors and you don't plan to be donating these to a library or

03:09.460 --> 03:21.620
something, comic books, if they're handled properly, are going to outlive you
most likely. So there's no real danger involved. They should be kept away from

03:21.620 --> 03:29.000
high humidity and excessive extremes of temperature and kept in a dry and cool
place and kept out of direct sunlight.

03:34.420 --> 03:42.620
Wayne pointed out to us that there's been a big change in the comic book
industry in the past few years, one that will affect collectors. The biggest

03:42.620 --> 03:51.740
thing that's happened in comic books recently, is probably the biggest thing
that's happened since comic books began, is that the ownership of some of the

03:51.740 --> 04:04.380
characters is now being held by the individual creators in much the same way
that a publisher does not own a novel by Isaac Asimov. Isaac Asimov would own

04:04.380 --> 04:14.240
the copyright. And now comic books are coming out where the writer or the artist
or both own the copyright to the character and the publisher is publishing it

04:14.240 --> 04:23.960
for them in the same kind of relationship that a book publisher has with a
novelist. And this is a complete change in the former system of the publisher

04:23.960 --> 04:32.500
owning everything, everything being done on a work-for-hire basis, as though the
artist was just coming in and doing the same type of function as sweeping the

04:32.500 --> 04:44.320
floors inside the corporate offices. This is going to be a change that's going
to become more and more evident in the next few years and is going to create a

04:44.320 --> 04:50.040
lot more excitement within the comic book field. We'll talk more about comics
with Bob Wayne on our next show.

