05:49.600 --> 05:53.520
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:09.420 --> 06:14.540
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:17.360 --> 06:18.860
And here are your hosts.

06:22.800 --> 06:29.660
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. We're talking with Bob Wayne, comic book
collector and owner of the Fantastic Worlds Bookstore in Fort Worth, Texas.

06:30.120 --> 06:37.800
Comic book collecting has become a rage recently. The prices of some collectible
comics have risen almost 1,000% in just a few years. On our last show, Bob Wayne

06:37.800 --> 06:45.080
explained some things about comic book collecting and advised the unwary
newcomer to be extremely cautious when entering the field. He also mentioned a

06:45.080 --> 06:52.200
big change that's taken place recently in the publishing of comic books. The one
who creates and draws a strip has complete rights over his work, just like the

06:52.200 --> 06:58.920
author of a novel. This means a comic book artist could change publishing
companies and move to where he can get the best contract. We asked Wayne what

06:58.920 --> 07:06.620
this change would mean to collectors, and he gave us an interesting answer. I
have to go back a little bit. The other thing that has changed the comic book

07:06.620 --> 07:17.340
industry is the change in distribution, where at one time all the comic books
pretty much were available at 7-11s and drugstores. And if 7-11 bought

07:17.340 --> 07:25.840
them from a distributor, the same people used it that handled TV Guide and Time
Magazine and such things, and they got a bundle of comic books in, and what they

07:25.840 --> 07:36.300
didn't sell they sent back for credit. And this meant that the publishers had to
print, just like on anything else, had to print, you know, let's say 500,000 and

07:36.300 --> 07:47.880
they sold 200,000, and 300,000 got thrown away. With the rise of specialty shops
that sell comic books and science fiction books, those shops order their comics

07:47.880 --> 07:56.920
in a different fashion. They order them non-returnable. They get a better
discount, but they have to keep everything they order. And it's now to the point

07:56.920 --> 08:06.020
where a lot of comic book titles are being published only in the non-returnable
format. So if a person's only buying their comic books at a 7-11 or in a

08:06.020 --> 08:12.800
small town that doesn't have a specialty store, there are a number of titles
they would never have seen. In fact, there are titles that are being published

08:12.800 --> 08:21.920
only for specialty store distribution that are selling better than some of the
comic books that have distribution in both forms. Examples of this would be

08:21.920 --> 08:33.220
Camelot 3000 from DC Comics, which takes the King Arthur saga and brings it back
to life, but in the year 3000. Starslayer from Pacific Comics, which is moving

08:33.220 --> 08:41.540
to another company called First Comics, which takes a man from out of the past
and springs him into the future, where he goes around and fights alien menaces

08:41.540 --> 08:53.480
and zooms from galaxy to galaxy. These titles are only published in specialty
stores. And the thing with a book like Starslayer, which is written and drawn

08:53.480 --> 09:04.880
by Mike Grell, who used to work for DC Comics doing The Warlord, is that Mike
Grell owns the copyright to Starslayer. And the fact that Mike Grell owns the

09:04.880 --> 09:14.020
copyright means that when his contract with the publisher Pacific Comics expired
with issue number six, he was able to find a better deal and make more money for

09:14.020 --> 09:20.440
himself and take it to First Comics, a new publishing company out of Chicago,
for starting with issue number seven.

09:31.420 --> 09:38.940
Wayne says this change, which allows a comic book character to switch publishing
companies, is a very recent one, and he likens it to the situation that exists

09:38.940 --> 09:48.620
in book publishing. The idea that a person could move a character from one
company to another for a better financial deal had never occurred to anyone a

09:48.620 --> 09:56.760
few years ago under the old system of publishing. But in the same way in book
publishing, that not every novel by an author necessarily is going to come out

09:56.760 --> 10:03.260
from the same publisher, there's no reason for every issue of a comic book to
come out from the same publisher. Some of the ramifications of this new

10:03.260 --> 10:09.980
situation should be obvious to collectors. One difference may well be that a
collector devoted to a particular character or artist will have to follow him

10:09.980 --> 10:17.280
through a number of publishing companies. Perhaps a collector will be required
to buy more issues, too, in order to acquire a complete set of something. Also,

10:17.420 --> 10:24.180
it should be more difficult to locate and catalog characters and artists, since
they will probably be spread out over more companies. But for dedicated comic

10:24.180 --> 10:31.300
book collectors, the new situation may be a beneficial one after all. Sure. With
more competition, there will likely be more comics and more artists, and

10:31.300 --> 10:33.220
therefore more material for collectors to work with.

