12:03.580 --> 12:05.200
And here are your hosts.

12:08.940 --> 12:17.060
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Poetry and science fiction, two unlikely
candidates for a merger, but they go together very well. As practitioners of the

12:17.060 --> 12:23.300
art and members of the Science Fiction Poetry Association will tell you. The
Science Fiction Radio Show spoke with some people in the Science Fiction Poetry

12:23.300 --> 12:31.060
Association about what exactly science fiction poetry is. Gene Van Troyer,
science fiction author and editor of a mainstream literary magazine, responds.

12:31.620 --> 12:40.540
Well, it's been around for quite a while. It's only been really in recent years
that the term science fiction poetry came into usage. I think about 1974 was

12:40.540 --> 12:51.260
when the term was first used, and it was coined by, well, it wasn't coined by
anybody, but it was just used as a label by Peter Dillingham, who was an early

12:51.260 --> 13:00.220
prosodist and theorist of science fiction poetry, and Stephen Gregg, who edited
Eternity Science Fiction, which was the first science fiction magazine to really

13:00.220 --> 13:11.040
incorporate poetry as an integral part of its format. What is science fiction
poetry? Well, I really can't say what science fiction poetry is in terms of a

13:11.040 --> 13:20.140
definition, because no one has ever defined science fiction or poetry. So
science fiction poetry has no real definition. But I generally tend to class

13:20.140 --> 13:32.860
science fiction poetry as something containing an element which is usually
associated with science fiction. In other words, speculative element of outer

13:32.860 --> 13:43.660
space or of biology or of time or whatnot. So that's my loose definition. It's
important to realize that what we now are calling science fiction poetry has

13:43.660 --> 13:54.400
been written in the so-called mainstream for a long time. William Blake is a
really primary example of someone who wrote mystical poetry, but in order to do

13:54.400 --> 14:06.380
it, he created alternate worlds and an ability to travel between this world or
the world of London that he knew and his imaginary England, which he called

14:06.380 --> 14:14.420
Albion. Well, that's fantasy. That's science fiction. That's alternate world
imagination.

14:16.680 --> 14:25.140
In more modern times, there's W.H. Auden, who has written a number of poems
which would be scientifically oriented, as well as science fictional, because

14:25.140 --> 14:37.320
they speculate about eventual results of scientific discoveries. One of the most
striking examples of what I would call science fiction poetry is something that

14:37.320 --> 14:45.240
was done by Richard Wilber, a well-established mainstream poet. And this poem is
called The Mind-Reader. Now, this is a poem about a person who actually reads

14:45.240 --> 14:52.280
minds, and he makes his living by reading minds. Now, I don't think Richard
Wilber would call it science fiction, although maybe in the back of his mind,

14:52.780 --> 15:01.440
he's working with the idea that, well, this is usually a science fiction theme.
But it's really a very well-done poem. And the point about science fiction

15:01.440 --> 15:12.240
poetry and mainstream poetry is that to be a good poem, a science fiction poem
must first be a good poem. And then, content-wise, it diverges from what we

15:12.240 --> 15:16.020
normally recognize or would normally class as mainstream poetry.

15:24.600 --> 15:33.100
The Science Fiction Poetry Association was founded in 1978 by Suzette Haden
Elgin, a mainstream novelist, who saw there was no meeting point for poets in

15:33.100 --> 15:39.320
the science fiction field. There are a number of well-known science fiction
writers who are members of the Science Fiction Poetry Association. Theodore

15:39.320 --> 15:46.820
Sturgeon, Ursula Le Guin, Gregory Benford, Ed Bryant, and Gene Wolfe are a few.
We asked Bob Frazier, editor of the Science Fiction Poetry Association

15:46.820 --> 15:56.840
newsletter, to tell us what the newsletter accomplishes. At the moment, the
newsletter seems to be the focus of the organization because we don't have any

15:56.840 --> 16:05.720
great amount of business that is important to us. We're sort of like a very
small non-profit organization, just basically people getting to know each other

16:05.720 --> 16:18.120
and setting up workshops at conventions, doing readings, teaching each other a
little bit about poetry, helping each other find good markets. We'll talk more

16:18.120 --> 16:19.940
about poetry and science fiction on our next show.

16:27.120 --> 16:34.960
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:34.960 --> 16:35.720
Odessa, Texas.

17:21.360 --> 17:25.280
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:40.960 --> 17:46.300
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

17:48.940 --> 17:50.640
And here are your hosts.

17:54.700 --> 18:02.100
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. We are speaking with some of the members
of the Science Fiction Poetry Association, practicing poets and science fiction

18:02.100 --> 18:09.520
authors who feel that poetry and science fiction go well together. We asked Bob
Frazier, editor of the Science Fiction Poetry Association newsletter, Starline,

18:09.680 --> 18:20.600
if most of the group's members are science fiction fans. It seems to work out
that way, but percentage-wise it's probably, well, 75%, I would say, but I

18:20.600 --> 18:29.620
should think it should be 90% in one sense, and I feel it shows that we do have
at least 25% membership of people who just are interested in poetry altogether,

18:30.520 --> 18:40.480
which is healthy. I mean, we're not trying to be separate from the mainstream of
literary mainstream with poetry, that's for sure. What's the difference between

18:40.480 --> 18:50.020
regular poetry and science fiction poetry? Well, there's several arguments about
that. I think my basic viewpoint is that if it's science fiction or fantasy

18:50.020 --> 18:59.580
poetry, if it's published within that genre, and because a lot of the poetry
really doesn't necessarily have to have unicorns or spaceships in it, a lot of

18:59.580 --> 19:12.020
it can be about very peripheral things. I'd call them speculative things. We
asked Frazier for an example of something speculative. Well, have you ever

19:12.020 --> 19:20.940
picked up a telephone and heard someone talking on the line somewhere far in the
distance? It's another conversation between two other people. Well, say you

19:20.940 --> 19:31.240
wrote a poem about that in the context of, like, there were telephone ghosts
that kind of live in the telephone line, okay? That would be a mainstream poem,

19:31.240 --> 19:41.220
or it could be a science fiction poem, because it deals sort of in that, the
same realm that imagination, that fantastic imagination is in.

19:48.540 --> 19:56.200
We asked Gene Van Troyer, science fiction poet and author, if there was anything
in style or technique that distinguished regular poetry from science fiction

19:56.200 --> 20:10.280
poetry. Any style can be used. You can use it in very rigidly metered and rhymed
poetic forms, which we usually call traditional poetic forms, sestinas, sonnets,

20:11.060 --> 20:23.380
villanils, and so forth, or it can use the free verse or the modern poetic
techniques that you would see, say, William Carlos Williams using or Charles

20:23.380 --> 20:32.320
Olson using. We asked Bob Frazier to give us some titles of books and magazines
that contain science fiction poetry. I suggest a book called Holding Your Eight

20:32.320 --> 20:42.680
Hands. It's been reprinted as a paperback by Doubleday last year. It originally
was published in 1969. The editor is Edward Lucy Smith, and it's a collection of

20:42.680 --> 20:52.160
science fiction poetry, an international collection, actually, although not
widely international, has British and, I think, some Australian authors and

20:52.160 --> 21:06.000
American authors in it. There's an anthology of poetry coming out from a man
here in Denver, Steve Rasnic Tem, and it's an offshoot of a magazine he's been

21:06.000 --> 21:16.080
editing of speculative poetry for three or four years. It's called the Umbral
Anthology, and it will use poetry out of what I see as the history of science

21:16.080 --> 21:27.080
fiction poetry. There's also, coming up, an anthology in a couple of years by
Bruce McAllister and Dick Allen, who are both writers of science fiction poetry

21:27.080 --> 21:35.820
and both people who work in academic jobs in the United States, which is going
to attempt to do the same thing, create a comprehensive anthology of some sort.

21:37.020 --> 21:49.260
And there is Starline, which is our newsletter, which publishes original poetry,
markets. We have a workshop in there. We have news related to science fiction

21:49.260 --> 21:58.960
and poetry. We have letter columns and everything that basically ties our
organization together. We'll conclude our discussion of science fiction and

21:58.960 --> 22:00.100
poetry on our next show.

22:06.860 --> 22:14.720
