Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:14.720 --> 22:15.480
Odessa, Texas.

23:03.060 --> 23:07.000
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:22.800 --> 23:28.000
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:30.780 --> 23:32.360
And here are your hosts.

23:36.240 --> 23:43.640
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. This will be our final show on science
fiction and poetry, and on the Science Fiction Poetry Association. The Science

23:43.640 --> 23:51.120
Fiction Poetry Association was founded as a formal organization in 1978. Its
members, which include some big-name science fiction authors, believe that

23:51.120 --> 23:58.760
science fiction and poetry are a natural blend. They publish a newsletter, meet
occasionally at science fiction conventions, read each other's poems, and help

23:58.760 --> 24:05.480
each other find markets for their work. Does science fiction poetry have
anything to offer that regular poetry doesn't? We asked this question of Bob

24:05.480 --> 24:17.320
Frazier, editor of the Science Fiction Poetry Association newsletter, Starline.
Yes. Today, science has found some things about the universe, especially let's

24:17.320 --> 24:27.840
use physics as an example, or found some things. Because science has become so
specialized, and that any scientist today is almost a specialist in his field,

24:28.100 --> 24:37.160
we are discovering the real depths of a lot of science, including psychology.
But let's pick physics, okay. They've come up against things like black holes,

24:37.360 --> 24:48.740
singularities, monopoles. And these are things which cannot be systematically
and rationally explained. And you will find in the scientific texts that are

24:48.740 --> 25:00.180
discussing these possibilities, these kind of rips in Einsteinian space-time
continuum, or however you want to look at them. They're anomalies. The science

25:00.180 --> 25:13.100
books are using, like Carl Sagan will use a poem, for example, to help explain,
to help visualize what it could possibly be or how it exists. And because poetry

25:13.100 --> 25:21.740
can, in a small space, deal with something which can be abstract, it doesn't
always have to be abstract, and it doesn't have to be unreadable, and it doesn't

25:21.740 --> 25:32.760
have to be boring, but because it can deal with some things that are abstract in
a small amount of space. Poetry can be, or poetic talk, even if it's in a prose

25:32.760 --> 25:38.660
sense, or even in a speech, can deal with abstract things nicely.

25:46.220 --> 25:53.400
Gene Van Troyer, author and poet in the science fiction field, sees science
fiction poetry as a significant recombining of two things that should go

25:53.400 --> 26:08.100
together. I think one thing that's important to distinguish also is that science
fiction poetry itself, I think represents a refusion of science and poetry. Up

26:08.100 --> 26:21.940
until the last decade, as a matter of fact, it was very voguish, very faddish
for poets and poetry-type people to view poetry and art and science as mutually

26:21.940 --> 26:33.540
exclusive. And this is a totally artificial separation, because poetic
expression comes from the same wellsprings that the ordering process we see in

26:33.540 --> 26:43.540
science comes from. It's the need to put order on the universe. Well, in the
Renaissance, you didn't see this really drastic split between science and art.

26:43.680 --> 26:51.620
They were viewed as being the same thing. But I mentioned William Blake earlier,
and it seems to me that around the time of William Blake, disillusionment with

26:51.620 --> 27:01.460
the Industrial Revolution and science was already setting in, and William Blake
is rabidly anti-science. And personally, I feel that he was mistaken in this

27:01.460 --> 27:11.440
particular aspect. But he looked around the world that he saw, and things were
terrible. People were enslaved almost by the industrial system, and he was just

27:11.440 --> 27:21.920
rabidly opposed to it because it oppressed the spirit. It oppressed the soul.
Well, now, I think this is a forerunner of the split that gradually grew from

27:21.920 --> 27:31.960
about the latter part of the 18th century up until the present time in the 20th
century. But it's gradually coming back together, and you see a lot more science

27:31.960 --> 27:40.120
showing up in poetry, and poets feeling much more confident about expressing
things out of science in their poetry, as well as scientists falling back on

27:40.120 --> 27:42.080
poetry to explicate things.

